description:
Germany is set to reintroduce voluntary military service for 18-year-olds from January under a new law.
The move is part of a wider push across Europe to increase conscription and defence readiness.
It comes as countries respond to growing security concerns linked to Russia’s war on Ukraine.
German officials say the scheme aims to strengthen the armed forces without full compulsory service.
The plan has sparked debate over youth participation, security needs and civil liberties.
Other European states are taking similar steps to boost troop numbers and preparedness.

Al Jazeera’s Dominic Kane reports from Berlin.

description:
Tens of thousands of jobs have been lost in Mexico in 2025 amid uncertainty over potential US tariffs.
President Donald Trump has extended a pause on 30 percent levies on Mexican goods, but businesses remain unable to plan.
Factories, especially along the US border, have cut jobs or consolidated operations as investors hesitate.
In cities like Ciudad Juárez, long-time factory workers have been laid off and are taking any work they can find.
More than 60,000 factory jobs have disappeared since 2023, leaving job fairs largely empty.
Industry leaders warn Mexico’s heavy reliance on US exports has made border economies especially vulnerable.

Al Jazeera’s Julia Galiano reports.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Vast crowds have gathered in the Bangladeshi capital Dhaka for the state funeral of former Prime Minister Khaleda Zia, with mourners travelling from across the country to bid farewell to a towering political leader.
Footage showed huge crowds streaming in towards the national parliament building on Manik Mia Avenue, where her coffin, draped in the national flag, was taken in a convoy on Wednesday. About 10,000 security personnel lined the streets to maintain order, officials said.
Zia’s body was then interred alongside her late husband, Ziaur Rahman, who was assassinated in 1981 during his time as president. Leaders and military officials laid wreaths as the burial took place.
Zia, the first woman to serve as prime minister in the South Asian nation when she became premier in 1991, died on Tuesday aged 79, after a prolonged illness.
Bangladesh has declared three days of state mourning, while tributes have flowed from world leaders as mourners farewell a politician viewed as a figurehe
title: Huge crowds for Khaleda funeral as Bangladesh bids farewell to ex-leader

description:
Saudi Arabia has released more details on the coalition bombing of the Yemeni port of Mukalla, which has triggered tensions with Gulf Arab neighbour the United Arab Emirates and prompted the latter to say it will withdraw its forces from Yemen.
Coalition spokesman Major-General Turki al-Maliki showed images documenting the military operation carried out early on Tuesday morning.
The UAE announced the withdrawal of its forces from Yemen, declaring an end to what it called “counterterrorism” operations there, after Riyadh accused Abu Dhabi of supporting separatists in Yemen.
The announcement on Tuesday came after Yemen’s internationally recognised government demanded the UAE pull its forces from the country within 24 hours, a call backed by Saudi Arabia.

Al Jazeera’s Michael Appel reports.
Hesham Alghannam is a Saudi scholar at the Malcolm Kerr Carnegie Middle East Center.
He says a red line was crossed, causing Riyadh to take action in Yemen.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Severe humanitarian needs in Gaza are worsening as dozens of aid groups are forced to halt operations under new Israeli restrictions.
Up to 48 organisations have stopped work, leaving fewer clinics, food distributions and shelters for civilians.
Aid agencies are described as the backbone of survival, providing medical care, clean water, protection and basic support.
Their absence also reduces visibility, as many groups document conditions and keep Gaza connected to the outside world.
Israel has long restricted international organisations, including UNRWA, accusing them of links to Hamas without providing evidence.
The UN and UNRWA have rejected these claims, saying safeguards are in place.
With displacement, hunger and disease rising, the measures risk deepening an already catastrophic crisis. 

Al Jazeera's Hani Mahmoud reports from Gaza City.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Bulgaria will become the 21st member of the eurozone – or Schengen monetary area – on Thursday, despite deep scepticism from some in the country amid fears of inflation.
The Southeast European country has been a member of the European Union since 2007, but formally met the eurozone’s entry criteria only in January 2025, paving the way for its currency ascension after a long delay.
The move will increase the number of Europeans using the euro to 356 million people, and geographically extend the single currency into the Black Sea area for the first time, despite ongoing geopolitical tensions.
However, there is concern among some Bulgarians that adopting the euro could bring on an economic crisis in a country considered the poorest in the EU.

Al Jazeera’s Step Vaessen reports from Sofia.

description:
It all began more than a decade ago.
Saudi Arabia and the United Arab Emirates were the pillars of a coalition created to fight the Houthis who had taken control in Yemen.
Over the years, that mission failed.
Then the UAE set out to pursue its own long-term interests, by supporting and arming a group called the Southern Transitional Council in the south of Yemen.
But Riyadh stepped in to disrupt what it saw as a national security threat, after the council took control of areas close to its borders.
The UAE was given 24 hours' notice to withdraw, that it agreed to.
What does all this mean for the future of Yemen?

Presenter: James Bays

Guests

Abdul-aziz Al Ghashian, Senior Non-Resident Fellow at Gulf International Forum.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Aaron David Miller, a former US Middle East negotiator and analyst, told Al Jazeera from Washington DC that US diplomacy has never applied democracy and human rights consistently.
He said that despite Donald Trump overturning many diplomatic norms, US alliances have not weakened and global leaders still seek engagement with Washington.
Miller noted that Middle Eastern leaders, including Israel’s partners, have imposed no real costs on the US or Israel over Gaza.
He dismissed claims of Trump-brokered peace deals, saying Iran saw only a temporary halt in fighting without diplomacy.
On Gaza, he said phase one of the ceasefire is in place but moving to phase two will be extremely difficult.
Miller warned Trump is overseeing an unprecedented expansion of presidential power that is undermining US democratic norms.
On Venezuela, he said Trump has left himself little room but to force Nicolás Maduro from power, risking US credibility if he fails.

Subscribe to our channel: http://bit.ly/AJSub
title: Why hasn’t the world pushed back against Trump? Aaron David Miller explains

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Thailand has released 18 Cambodian soldiers it captured in July as part of a new ceasefire deal.  
A large crowd greeted the soldiers as they arrived in Cambodia's western Pailin province.
Both countries signed the ceasefire on Saturday.  
The agreement ended three weeks of renewed cross-border fighting that killed more than a hundred people and displaced around a million. 

Al Jazeera’s Assed Baig has more from Cambodia’s Banteay Meanchey province, near the border with Thailand.

Ja Ian Chong is Associate Professor of political science at the National University of Singapore.
He says the dispute between Thailand and Cambodia runs deep and the potential for hostilities remain.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Iran says it is seeking dialogue with protest leaders after a third day of unrest, sparked by a record drop in the national currency's value. 
Demonstrations began on Sunday after shopkeepers in Tehran's Grand Bazaar walked off the job.
University students have joined in on the rallies. 
Demonstrations have now spread to several cities across the country with residents angered by the high cost of living. 

Trita Parsi is the executive vice president of the Quincy Institute for Responsible Statecraft. 
He says the population doesn't have faith in the government's ability to handle the economic crisis.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Guinea has declared military ruler Mamady Dumbuya the winner of Sunday's presidential election. 
He seized power in a 2021 coup.
Provisional results say Dumbuya won in a landslide, receiving nearly 87 percent of the vote. 
Opponents have called the election a sham.

Al Jazeera’s Ahmed Idris reports from Guinea's capital Conakry.
